Tepco estimates that around 1,000 tons of groundwater flow through the site every day, some 400 tons of which goes into the radioactive reactor buildings. It is mixed with another 400 tons injected daily to keep the melted fuel cores cool. The company was pumping out that water every day, recycling half and putting the other half in storage, while it hurried to figure out ways of keeping the groundwater from getting contaminated in the first place, Tepco and government officials said.
